// ch05 §5.12: "Reuses real C++ lambda syntax verbatim ... including
// `mutable`." By default a closure's `operator()` is const (a by-value
// capture can't be reassigned inside the body); `mutable` opts out,
// matching real C++. Mutating the closure's own copy must not affect the
// outer `x` (a separate, by-value-captured member) -- computed as
// `mutated_copy * 10 + outer_x` in one expression so both are observable
// from a single exit code: inner lambda returns 6 (5+1), outer `x` stays
// 5, so 6*10+5 = 65.
int main() {
    int x = 5;
    return [x]() mutable { x = x + 1; return x; }() * 10 + x;
}
